content: 10However, this [2]catenane is unsuitablefor use as a receptor, because it con tains two mutually interlockedcages whose cavities are already occupied by each other. In an effortto address this deficiency, we have used a hydrazone-based DCCapproach to produce a triangular prism-shaped cage by condensingcarbonyl dihydrazine11Hand a trialdehyde precursor10A3+in water(Fig. 1). This cage acts as a molecular flask to accommodate suitablypaired donor每acceptor substrates, such as guests containing eitherdihydroxynaphthalene or naphthalene diimide. The intermoleculardonor每acceptor interactions between these two guests are remark-ably enhanced within the cage cavity. It was found that cageformation is highly favored at elevated temperatures due to entropiceffects, while at lower temperatures substantial amounts of polymersor oligomers are also generated as byproducts. The kinetics ofhydrazone formation and disassembly were also found to betemperature dependent. Coolin g the system to room temperatureswitches ＆＆off＊＊ the hydrazone bond exchange, and locks the cagearchitecture. Thus, cage products obtained at higher temperaturecould be effectively ＆＆caught＊＊ at l ower temperatures and maintainedfor several days at room temperature without appreciable decom-position. Two precursors, namely the aldehyde derivative A3+/C13Cl/C0andcarbonyl dihydrazine H, were both synthesized from commerciallyavailable compounds viaone-step procedures (see the ESI ?). Bothof these precursors are soluble in aqueous medium, presumablyd u et ot h ep r e s e n c eo ft h ep y r i d inium and amino functionalgroups, respectively. Mixing A3+/C13Cl/C0(3.1 mg, 4.0 mmol) and H(0.54 mg, 6.0 mmol) in D 2O (1 mL) in the presence of a catalyticamount of deuterated TFA (0.4 mmol) led at early times to a libraryof intractable oligomeric or polym eric products, as inferred from1H NMR spectral analyses (see Fig. S3 in the ESI ?). The formation of C6+is also supported by theDOSY NMR spectrum (Fig. S4, ESI ?) and mass spectrometricanalysis (Fig. S5, ESI ?). For instance, prominent peaks corres-ponding to [M + nCl](6/C0n)+(n= 1每3) were clearly observed in themass spectrum, which confirms that the condensation of A3+andHoccurred in a [2+3] manner.

This self-assembled cage acts as an e?ective receptor for donor每acceptor pairs,whose interactions are weak in the absence of the cage.

In order to shed more light on thearchitecture of the cage C6+, we synthesized a bis-hydrazone com-pound, namely, S2+/C12PF 6/C0( F i g .2 a ) ,b yc o n d e n s i n g Hwith cationicmethylpyridinium-4-carboxalde hyde in a [1+2] manner (see Fig. S1and S2 in the ESI ?). This bishydrazone derivative S2+could beconsidered as an analog of three bishydrazone fragmental ＆＆walls＊＊ ofthe cage C6+. The single crystal of S2+/C12PF 6/C0w a so b t a i n e db ys l o wdi?usion of isopropyl ether into a solution of S2+/C12PF 6/C0in acetoni-trile. The solid-state structure of S2+demonstrates (Fig. 2a) thatwithin the carbonyl dihydrazone residue, one of the two hydrazonenitrogen atoms undergoes intramolecular hydrogen bonding withthe amide proton that is connected to another hydrazone, whichresults in a bent conformation of S2+. Also thanks to the intra-molecular hydrogen bonding, the moiety of S2+in the solid state hasa close to flat conformation. In the cage framework of C6+,t h i spreorganized conformation might help to suppress the formation ofoligomeric or polymeric byproducts in self-assembly. (see Fig. S22, ESI ?). The implication is that the formationof an alternative [2+3] condensation product of C6+,n a m e l y P6+(see Fig. 2b), is energy demanding or might be even impossible.

A number of factors could contribute to the high yield of cageformation. First, the dynamic nature of the hydrazone bond in C6+at elevated temperatures allows the system to undergo errorchecking, allowing the components to ＆＆search＊＊ for the thermo-dynamic minimum. Compared to the polymeric and oligomericbyproducts, the self-assembled cage C6+contains a minimal [2+3]number of components and therefore, necessarily represents themost entropically favored product.12The entropic driving force forcage formation, compared to its byproducts, is enhanced at highertemperatures, given the fact that DG=DH/C0TDS. This, we believe,accounts for the high yield synthesis of the cage product seen atelevated temperatures.
